  "messages": [
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "contents": [
        {
          "$type": "text",
          "text": "{\"adaptation_kind\":\"Restructure\",\"safety_tier\":\"Green\",\"nudge_patch\":null,\"restructure_plan\":{\"revised_weekly_targets\":[{\"week_number\":1,\"weekly_target_km\":46},{\"week_number\":2,\"weekly_target_km\":50},{\"week_number\":3,\"weekly_target_km\":55}],\"revised_current_week_workouts\":[{\"day_of_week\":2,\"workout_type\":\"Easy\",\"title\":\"Easy Aerobic Flush\",\"target_distance_km\":8,\"target_duration_minutes\":48,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":360,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":360,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":5,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":370,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Start very gently — just get the blood moving, no agenda on pace.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":38,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":360,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Hold a truly conversational effort throughout. If you feel the urge to push, back off — this run is about flushing residual fatigue, not building fitness.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":5,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":375,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Walk the final 2 minutes if the legs still feel heavy.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"5 minutes at a very easy jog to open up the legs before settling into your easy rhythm.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"Easy jog to a walk. Spend 5 minutes on light leg swings and calf stretches.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"The sole purpose of this run is recovery and movement. Keep effort well within your easy Daniels-Gilbert zone — heart rate conversational the whole way. There is no pace target to chase today.\",\"perceived_effort\":4},{\"day_of_week\":4,\"workout_type\":\"Tempo\",\"title\":\"Moderate Tempo Progression\",\"target_distance_km\":10,\"target_duration_minutes\":52,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":360,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":295,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":12,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":360,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Easy jog warmup — let the pace come to you naturally, don't force it.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":28,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":295,\"intensity\":\"Threshold\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Aim for a comfortably hard effort — you should be able to speak a short phrase but not hold a conversation. This is a softer threshold prescription than the original session, giving you room to find the effort without straining.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":12,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":360,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Easy jog cooldown, fully flushing the tempo effort before you stop.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"12 minutes easy jog. Optionally include 3–4 light strides in the final 2 minutes to gently prime the legs.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"12 minutes easy, then 5 minutes walking and dynamic stretching.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"This is a reduced-intensity version of the originally planned threshold session. Rather than targeting the full prescribed threshold band, you are working at a slightly eased pace-zone index to let the body find its rhythm again. Success here means finishing feeling controlled and confident, not spent.\",\"perceived_effort\":6},{\"day_of_week\":6,\"workout_type\":\"LongRun\",\"title\":\"Aerobic Long Run — Rebuilding Confidence\",\"target_distance_km\":16,\"target_duration_minutes\":97,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":360,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":355,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":10,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":370,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"First 10 minutes very easy — resist any urge to settle into long-run pace early.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":77,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":357,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Steady aerobic effort in the easy Daniels-Gilbert zone throughout. The distance is deliberately shorter than originally scheduled — treat that as a feature, not a compromise.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":10,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":370,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Back off the pace for the final 10 minutes and finish feeling like you have something left.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"10 minutes very easy jogging before settling into long-run rhythm.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"5-minute walk followed by thorough hip flexor, quad, and calf stretches.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"This long run is scaled back to 16 km to allow genuine recovery while maintaining the aerobic stimulus. Keeping the full distance from last week's aborted effort would risk compounding fatigue. Aim to finish this run feeling strong — that sensation is the most important training output of the day.\",\"perceived_effort\":6}],\"forward_path\":\"From here the path back is steady and intentional. Week 2 brings the volume up to around 50 km, with the intervals reintroduced at a shorter rep prescription (4 of 6) to rebuild confidence at quality pace before asking for the full set. Week 3 moves to 55 km with the full interval session restored and the long run stepping back up toward 20 km. By Week 4 you would be back at — or very close to — the original meso targets, having rebuilt on a solid foundation rather than fighting through accumulated fatigue. Consistency across these three weeks is what earns the fitness, not any single session.\"},\"net_load_delta\":-14,\"rationale\":\"Shutting it down after three reps on Saturday was exactly the right call — listening to your body in that moment takes more discipline than grinding through a bad session, and it gives us genuinely useful information about where your fatigue is right now. Looking at the pattern across the last three sessions together — the tempo pace sitting about 40 seconds per kilometre softer than your threshold band, the intervals stopping at the halfway point, and the long run cut short — what that picture suggests is accumulated fatigue that has built up faster than the plan anticipated. The body simply hasn't had enough recovery to absorb the load at full intensity yet. What I've changed: this week's volume comes down to around 46 km, the tempo session on Thursday uses a slightly eased pace-zone index to let you find a controlled, confident threshold effort rather than straining for the full band, and Saturday's long run is scaled to 16 km — a distance you can finish feeling strong. The intervals are rested this week entirely. From there the path forward is a gentle staircase: 50 km in Week 2 with a shorter interval set reintroduced, 55 km in Week 3 with the full interval session restored and the long run stepping back toward 20 km, and by Week 4 you would be back at the original meso targets. Three weeks of consistent, absorbed training will do far more for your sub-3:15 goal than trying to claw back missed volume in a single session.\",\"referral_category\":null}"
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
